				<div class="comment-content"><blockquote>
<p><a class="mention" href="https://forum.quillette.com/u/quillette">@quillette</a>: One of the comforts of studying history is that, no matter how bad things get, you can always find a moment in the past when things were much, much worse.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>How true. And even if Corona turns out to be the most severe pandemic we have experienced in a century, we should not forget that fortunately our starting point in terms of knowledge, technology, communication, wealth and medicine is the highest that humans have ever experienced in all recorded and unrecorded history. If people from the plague-stricken Middle Ages were brought into the present with a time machine, they would probably sigh with relief and praise heaven for the change, despite the spreading Corona threat.</p>
<p>I hope that we as a society will overcome the crisis in such a way that we prove ourselves worthy of this privileged starting position. So far, the Western countries in particular have not exactly covered themselves in glory. More than two months of advance warning have been wasted instead of being used for emergency preparations and containment. Now, finally, everyone is trying to catch up. But the late start now makes much stronger countermeasures necessary, which in turn will most likely sow the seeds for a severe economic crisis. Maybe future generations will find the term <em>The Sleepwalkers</em> appropriate to describe how we managed to get ourselves into such a mess.</p>
</div>
